# Element ID & Name Standards

## test-id

Every interactive or form element **must** have a unique `test-id` attribute.

- Format: `kebab-case`, scoped to the feature (e.g., `campaign-name-input`, `submit-button`)
- Never reuse the same `test-id` on two elements within the same page/view
- `test-id` is a GLOBAL attribute — place it before other non-structural attributes per `vue/attributes-order`

```vue
<!-- ✅ CORRECT -->
<input
  test-id="campaign-name-input"
  name="campaignName"
  type="text"
/>

<button test-id="campaign-submit-btn" type="submit">Save</button>

<!-- ❌ WRONG — missing test-id -->
<button type="submit">Save</button>
```

## Button Type

Every `<button>` **must** have an explicit `type` attribute (`button`, `submit`, or `reset`). ESLint rule `vue/html-button-has-type` enforces this.

```vue
<!-- ✅ CORRECT -->
<button type="button" @click="handleCancel">Cancel</button>
<button type="submit">Save</button>

<!-- ❌ WRONG — implicit type -->
<button @click="handleCancel">Cancel</button>
```

## Form Field Names

Form inputs inside a `<form>` **must** also have a `name` attribute matching the field key sent to the backend.

```vue
<form @submit.prevent="handleSubmit">
  <input
    test-id="email-input"
    name="email"
    type="email"
  />
</form>
```

## Accessibility

- `<a>` tags used as buttons need `tabindex="0"`, `role="button"`, `aria-label`, and keyboard handlers.
- Use semantic HTML first; avoid ARIA overrides when native elements suffice.
